      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq">
          <h3>Do I need to hold 30 seconds before starting the 8-week program?</h3>
          <p>Yes, a 30-second overhand dead hang is the minimum entry point. This baseline confirms your grip and shoulder joints can handle the increased volume of 4 sessions per week. Complete the 4-week beginner program first if you fall short of 30 seconds.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq">
          <h3>Why does the program use three different grip types?</h3>
          <p>Overhand, underhand and neutral grips each stress different forearm and finger muscles. Rotating grips prevents adaptation plateaus and builds balanced grip endurance. Most people hold 10-15% longer with underhand grip, so variety also reveals hidden capacity.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq">
          <h3>What are active hangs and why are they included in weeks 7-8?</h3>
          <p>Active hangs keep your arms straight while engaging the scapulae by pulling shoulder blades down and back. They build the shoulder stability needed for advanced hang variations and pull-up progressions. The program introduces them late because they require a solid endurance base first.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq">
          <h3>What should I do if I plateau at 45 seconds during the program?</h3>
          <p>Reduce the last two sets to 80% of your max instead of failing early. Building total time under tension matters more than hitting exact numbers every set. If the plateau persists for 2 weeks, drop rest periods from 90 to 60 seconds to force adaptation through increased metabolic stress.</p>
        </div>

